<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870626-0011 </DOCNO><HL> Banks in Oklahoma,Colorado Are Closed</HL><DD> 06/26/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> GOVMTBANKS, THRIFT INSTITUTIONS (BNK)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two banks, one in Colorado and the other in Oklahoma, were closed yesterday, bringing the number of bank failures nationwide this year to 94, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said.    South Denver National Bank, Glendale, Colo., was closed by the Comptroller of the Currency and the FDIC was named receiver. South Denver's deposits of $47.7 million in 7,500 accounts were assumed by First National Bank of Southeast Denver, Denver, Colo., and its two offices will reopen today as offices of First National. The failed bank's assets totaled $54.4 million.    First National agreed to pay the FDIC a $1.6 million purchase premium and will buy certain loans and other assets totaling $32 million. The FDIC said it will advance $20.7 million to First National and will retain assets totaling $22.4 million.    South Denver National was the seventh Colorado bank to fail this year.    The FDIC also said that Eighty Niner Bank of Coyle, Coyle, Okla., was closed by state banking officials, bringing the number of Oklahoma bank failures this year to 14.    Eighty Niner Bank's only office will reopen today as a branch of Oklahoma State Bank of Mulhall. Oklahoma State Bank is assuming the failed bank's deposits of $5.4 million in 1,200 accounts and is purchasing $3.9 million of Eighty Niner's $5.9 million in loans and other assets. </TEXT></DOC>